In [21]:
# Plot the statistical significance of principal components for the model building

with plt.style.context('dark_background'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

    plt.bar(range(len(eigenvalues)), varariance, alpha=0.8, align='center',
            label='individual explained variance')
    plt.ylabel('Explained variance ratio')
    plt.xlabel('Principal components')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.tight_layout()

From the above plot we can see that after 360 components, the variation explained by principal components is almost zero. Moreover, majority of the variation in the data is explained by first 100 components. Hence, I am considering first 100 components for the classification model building.

# Performing Cross validation on SVM Classification model

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, KFold

# Finding the accuracy score on cross validation

cross_val_scores = cross_val_score(svm_classifier, X_train, y_train, cv=KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=16))
print("Cross-validation accuracy scores:", cross_val_scores)
print("Mean accuracy:", cross_val_scores.mean())

from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer

# Define the precision scoring metric
precision_scorer = make_scorer(precision_score, average='weighted') # The average ='weighted' will consider the class imbalance.

# Perform cross-validation with precision scoring
cross_val_scores = cross_val_score(svm_classifier, X_train, y_train, cv=KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=16), scoring=precision_scorer)

# Print the cross-validation scores
print("Cross-validation precision scores:", cross_val_scores)
print("Mean precision:", cross_val_scores.mean())

# Calculating the recall score using cross validation

scoring = make_scorer(recall_score, average='macro') # average='macro': The recall score is calculated for each class individually, and then the average of these scores is computed. It gives equal weight to each class, regardless of class imbalance.

recall_scores = cross_val_score(svm_classifier, X_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring=scoring)

# Print the recall scores for each fold
print("Cross-validation Recall Scores:", recall_scores)

# Calculate the mean recall score
mean_recall_score = recall_scores.mean()
print("Mean Recall Score:", mean_recall_score)

Conclusion¶

As part of this project, the parkinson's speech dataset was imported from UCI machine learning repository. Data Preprocessing and Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) technique applied on the raw data to have better understanding of the dataset. As the number of columns is too large, we applied principal component analysis on the standardized feature matrix and selected first 100 components that are explaining almost 90% of variation in the data. Support Vector Machine Algorithm is used for classification model building.

We have developed 2 classification models using support vector machines algorithm:

  1. Support Vector Classifier model trained on first 100 components of PCA
  2. Support Vector Classifier model trained on the entire standardized feature matrix

The observations are:

  • The accuracy of SVM classifier with 100 PCA components is 79.97%
  • The accuracy of SVM classifier with standardized original data is 80.63%

  • The Precision of SVM classifier with 100 PCA components is 79.74%
  • The Precision of SVM classifier with standardized original data is 80.65%

  • The Recall of SVM classifier with 100 PCA components is 76.66%
  • The Recall of SVM classifier with standardized original data is 75.33%

The above results indicates that there is not much difference in performance of models trained with PCA and without PCA. Though, the performance seems to be slightly better with entire data, the model becoming overfitted due to large number of features, out of which many of them are not contributing to the model prediction and introducing noise into the model functioning. Hence, it is better to use the SVM classifier model trained on first 100 PCA components as it is providing better recall value for identifying parkinson's disease.
